–1488":"1430–1488","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1442–Male":"1442–Deceased","1449–Male":"1449–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1478–1527":"1478–1527","1479–1501":"1479–1501","1481–1521":"1481–1521","1402–1485":"1402–1485","1420–1449":"1420–1449","1481":"1481","Abt 1449":"about 1449","1479":"1479","1402":"1402","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1521":"1521","1488":"1488","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","about 1430":"about 1430","1527":"1527","1449":"1449","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","North Mymms, Hertfordshire, England":"North Mymms, Hertfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Knollys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Knowles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knowles","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>knol(le)</i> ‘knoll, hilltop’ (Old English <i>cnoll</i>) or from any of the many places (some lost) named with this word, for example Knowle (Devon, Dorset, Lancashire, Somerset, Warwickshire, and Yorkshire) and Knole (Kent, Sussex).","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tnúthghail</b> (see   Newell  ).","English: variant of   Noel  , often, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Knollys was born about 1449, his father, Sir Richard Knollys, was 48 and his mother, Margaret d'Oyley, was 30. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Elizabeth Troutbeck."},"et":{"Abt 1449–":"umbes 1449–Surnud","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1442–Male":"1442–Surnud","1449–Male":"1449–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1478–1527":"1478–1527","1479–1501":"1479–1501","1481–1521":"1481–1521","1402–1485":"1402–1485","1420–1449":"1420–1449","1481":"1481","Abt 1449":"umbes 1449","1479":"1479","1402":"1402","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1521":"1521","1488":"1488","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1527":"1527","1449":"1449","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","North Mymms, Hertfordshire, England":"North Mymms, Hertfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1449–":"noin 1449–Kuollut","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1442–Male":"1442–Kuollut","1449–Male":"1449–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1478–1527":"1478–1527","1479–1501":"1479–1501","1481–1521":"1481–1521","1402–1485":"1402–1485","1420–1449":"1420–1449","1481":"1481","Abt 1449":"noin 1449","1479":"1479","1402":"1402","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1521":"1521","1488":"1488","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","about 1430":"noin 1430","1527":"1527","1449":"1449","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","North Mymms, Hertfordshire, England":"North Mymms, Hertfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1449–":"environ 